Step 5 Summary of aspects of the datasets that are most relevant for statistical analyses

Upper limit: 1 page of text (or about 1/3 page per dataset)

Stream water chemistry data (1992-2015)

When, Where and How was the data collected

Dip samples are used to measure the stream water chemistry and are collected weekly. (specific date, hour and minute will be included in the Supporting Documentation)

The data is collected at designated ECN sites across the UK, representing different landscapes and ecosystems. (Including T02:Glensaugh, T04: Moor House - Upper Teesdale, T05: North Wyke, T06: Rothamsted, T07: Sourhope, T08: Wytham, T11: Y Wyddfa – Snowdon, T12: Cairngorms)

Samples are sent to accredited laboratories for chemical analysis. Measured variables include: nutrients (nitrate, ammonium, phosphate), metals (iron, aluminium), pH, Conductivity etc.

As a quality check, a standard quality control solution is sent to the laboratories that analyse the ECN water samples. This solution is analysed alongside the samples collected in the field.

Multiple levels of quality control were applied: Quality Codes

Why was the data collected

Monitor water quality over time: by tracking concentrations of key chemical molecules. This detects long term trand and seasonal change within UK and for different UK sites. This could also monitor the health of ecosystem and pollution level which would be able to aid regulatory and policy makings.

Precipitation chemistry data (1992-2015)

When, Where and How was the data collected

Bulk collectors are used to measure the precipitation chemistry. The samples are collected weekly. The data was collected weekly spanning 1992 to 2015. (specific date, hour and minute will be included in the Supporting Documentation)

The data was collected from 12 terrestrial ECN sites across the UK, including upland and lowland regions. This includes Drayton, Glensaugh, Hillsborough, Moor House – Upper Teesdale, North Wyke, Rothamsted, Sourhope, Wytham, Alice Holt, Porton Down, Y Wyddfa – Snowdon, Cairngorms, with site codes T01 to T12 respectively.

Samples were analysed for a wide range of chemical variables including major cations and anions (such as [Ca²⁺], [Mg²⁺], [NH₄⁺], [NO₃⁻], [SO₄²⁻]), and dissolved molecules (e.g. phosphate).

As a quality check, a standard quality control solution is sent to the laboratories that analyse the ECN water samples. This solution is analysed alongside the samples collected in the field.

Multiple levels of quality control were applied: Quality Codes

Why was the data collected

The data is able tto help us to identify atmospheric pollution level and trends by monitoring the deposition of pollutants.

It also support long-term environmental monitoring as it provides a long term yet consistent data regarding the eco-system which could help policy makers to evaluate the severity of climate change and take this information into consideration.

Soil solution chemistry data (1992-2015)

When, Where and How was the data collected

Suction samplers are used to measure the soil solution chemistry. The samples are collected fortnightly.

Occasionally suction samplers need to be replaced. This will be indicated by a new RID (replicate ID) in the dataset.

If insufficient sample is collected by the individual samplers, then the samples for that sampling day can be bulked. This will be indicated by the RID – ‘XXS’ for shallow samplers and ‘XXD’ for deep samplers.

Key variables measured include: nutrients (NO₃N, NH₄N) metals (Aluminium, Iron) pH, DOC, conductivity residual vacuum, and more.

As a quality check, a standard quality control solution is sent to the laboratories that analyse the ECN water samples. This solution is analysed alongside the samples collected in the field.

The data was collected from 12 terrestrial ECN sites across the UK, including upland and lowland regions. This includes Drayton, Glensaugh, Hillsborough, Moor House – Upper Teesdale, North Wyke, Rothamsted, Sourhope, Wytham, Alice Holt, Porton Down, Y Wyddfa – Snowdon, Cairngorms, with site codes T01 to T12 respectively.

Why was the data collected

To monitor the long term change in soil water chemistry, including chemical pollution, soil health, potentially for agrculture by using consistent standard methods. To study the affects caused by potential land use changes, xlimate change, acidification etc. to support government policy.

  # Create a new column "Month" by extracting the year and month from the SDATE column

  # Count the number of records for each Month value

  # Create a line plot using ggplot2

library(tidyverse)

# Stream Water
# Prepare the data for plotting
df_stream_missing <- df_stream_wide %>%
  select(SDATE, where(is.numeric), -LCODE) %>%   # Keep SDATE + numeric columns (drop things like SITECODE), remove LCODE only for the stream water dataframe since it is numeric
  pivot_longer(-SDATE, names_to = "Variables", values_to = "Value") %>%
  mutate(Missing = is.na(Value)) %>%
  arrange(SDATE) %>%
  mutate(Row = as.numeric(factor(SDATE, levels = unique(SDATE))))

# Year break lines for visual clarity
year_breaks_stream <- df_stream_missing %>%
  distinct(SDATE, Row) %>%
  mutate(Year = as.numeric(format(SDATE, "%Y"))) %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise(Row = min(Row), .groups = "drop")

# Plot
ggplot(df_stream_missing, aes(x = Variables, y = Row, fill = Missing)) +
  geom_tile(color = NA) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("FALSE" = "grey80", "TRUE" = "black")) +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  geom_hline(data = year_breaks_stream, aes(yintercept = Row), color = "red", linewidth = 0.3) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    breaks = year_breaks_stream$Row + 10,  # adjust this based on your density
    labels = year_breaks_stream$Year,
    expand = c(0, 0)
  ) +
  labs(title = "Missing Data Heatmap: Stream Water Chemistry Over Time",
       x = "Variables", y = "Year", fill = "Missing")+
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
## Scale for y is already present.
## Adding another scale for y, which will replace the existing scale.

Soil solution

Uniqueness: From the r code to check for the number of duplicated row, we can see that the dataframe has a uniqueness of 100%.

Consistency: consistent

Timeliness: The range is from the 6th of October 1992 to the 23rd of December 2015, which is valid even though it ends earlier compared to the previous dataframes, since this is only sampled fortnightly.

From the Sample Frequency plot, we note that we may have different no. weeks in a month, thus resulting the fluctuation. The frequency started low, though slowly increasing after 1995. However, the frequency started to decrease after 2010.

Validity: Valid since no out of range value and false formatting was spotted.

Accuracy: Accurate as it matches reality

User needs and trade-offs: Policymakers may want long-term trends to help them make policies. Scientists may need long-term trends to study environmental change, which is critical with regards to climate change.

Completeness: The data is way less complete in comparison to the previous two comparison, with more black (missing data) than grey (completed data). Overall, the completeness varies across the the years and variables: with PHAQCS (Aquacheck system pH stirred), PHAQCU (Aquacheck system pH unstirred), and TOTALP (Total dissolved phosphorus) barely having any completion, while it has little completion in the second half of 1990s, 2001, 2003, 2008 and 2014-2015. However, two sets of variables are almost complete, which are: VACUUM (Residual vacuum at time of sampling) and VOLUME (Volume of sample collected)
